<DOC><DOCNO> AP890824-0233 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 1431EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     08-24 0274</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0289</SECOND><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The stock market surged ahead today, making a newrun toward record highs in a carryover of buying from Wednesday'ssession.   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up 27.12 pointsWednesday, jumped 33.57 to 2,711.68 by 2 p.m. today on Wall Street.   The average's record close of 2,722.42 was set Aug. 25, 1987.   Gainers outnumbered losers by more than 5 to 2 in nationwidetrading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 1,050 up, 385down and 488 unchanged.   Analysts said the market benefited from a downturn in interestrates that began Wednesday. Rates declined slightly in erratictrading today.   Brokers also said buying was encouraged by a continuing flow ofdevelopments and rumors on the mergers and acquisitions front.   In the latest deal, Holiday Corp. said it will sell its HolidayInn hotel system to Bass PLC for $2.23 billion and create asubsidiary to operate its gaming operations and three newer hotelbrands. Holiday shares jumped 7{ to 84{.   In addition, big-name stocks got a boost at midday from a wave ofbuying by professional traders engaged in computer-programstrategies involving stock index options and futures.   Gainers among the blue chips included General Motors, up 1} at46\; International Business Machines, up 1[ at 115[; DuPont, up 2[at 119|, and American Telephone andamp; Telegraph, up 1 at 39|.   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose2.13 to 193.97. At the American Stock Exchange, the market valueindex was up 2.62 at 380.32.   Volume on the Big Board came to 159.69 million shares with twohours to go.</TEXT></DOC>